&lt;p>the code is really simple, first of all if the image is not contained in a div I wrap it into a div. This can change a little the layout of the page, so I suggest for every image that need to be swapped with another image to be originally enclosed in a div to make the transition happens. Next I set the new image as the div background, set the background-repeat to &lt;em>no repeat&lt;/em>, then fade out the original image. When the original image fades out it slowly merge with the new image into the background. Finally when the fading out is completed I change the source of the image and finally show the image again.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>JQuery your first plugin</title><link>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/03/jquery-your-first-plugin/</link><pubDate>Sat, 28 Mar 2009 04:00:37 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/03/jquery-your-first-plugin/</guid><description>&lt;p>One of the most interesting feature of JQuery is its extendibility. Writing a plugin is a breeze, and here an example of your first &lt;a href="http://jquery.com/">JQuery&lt;/a> plugin, a logger to the &lt;a href="http://getfirebug.com/">firebug&lt;/a> console.&lt;/p>
